# 🔐 Encrypted USB Backup Drive Setup (LUKS2 + ext4)

A guide to formatting a USB drive with strong LUKS2 encryption using argon2id — the same KDF used for hardened Linux system drives.

---

## Why LUKS2 + argon2id?

| | LUKS1 (GNOME Disks default) | LUKS2 + argon2id (this guide) |
|---|---|---|
| KDF | PBKDF2 | argon2id |
| GPU brute-force resistance | Weak | Strong (memory-hard) |
| Unlock time | ~0.5s | ~4s |
| Read/write speed after unlock | Normal | Identical |

> **argon2id** is memory-hard, meaning brute-force attacks via GPU/ASIC are significantly more expensive. The 4 second unlock delay only happens once when mounting — file transfers are unaffected.

---

## Prerequisites

- `cryptsetup` installed (`sudo apt install cryptsetup` on Debian/Ubuntu)
- Your USB drive identified — use `lsblk` to confirm the device name before proceeding

```bash
lsblk
```

> ⚠️ **Double-check your device name.** This guide uses `/dev/sdb`. Substitue with your actual device. Running `luksFormat` on the wrong drive will wipe it.

---

## How it works

```
/dev/sdb  →  LUKS2 container  →  ext4 filesystem inside
```

LUKS wraps the entire drive first, then ext4 lives inside the encrypted container. The order matters — LUKS goes on before formatting.

---

## Setup Steps

### 1. Write the LUKS2 container to the drive

```bash
sudo cryptsetup luksFormat --type=luks2 --pbkdf argon2id --iter-time 4000 /dev/sdb
```

- You will be prompted to type `YES` (in caps) to confirm
- Then set and confirm your passphrase — **use a strong one, there's no recovery if you forget it**

### 2. Open / unlock the container

```bash
sudo cryptsetup open /dev/sdb Backup-Linux
```

This creates a decrypted device at `/dev/mapper/Backup-Linux`.

### 3. Format the decrypted device as ext4

```bash
sudo mkfs.ext4 /dev/mapper/Backup-Linux
```

### 4. Mount it (optional — to verify or start using it)

```bash
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/Backup-Linux
sudo mount /dev/mapper/Backup-Linux /mnt/Backup-Linux
```

### 5. Close / lock the drive when done

```bash
sudo umount /mnt/Backup-Linux
sudo cryptsetup close Backup-Linux
```

---

## Everyday Use

After setup, GNOME Files (Nautilus) will automatically prompt for your passphrase when you plug in the drive and handle mounting/unmounting. No terminal needed for day-to-day use.

To mount manually:

```bash
sudo cryptsetup open /dev/sdb Backup-Linux
sudo mount /dev/mapper/Backup-Linux /mnt/Backup-Linux
```

To unmount manually:

```bash
sudo umount /mnt/Backup-Linux
sudo cryptsetup close Backup-Linux
```

---

## Optional: Even Stronger Encryption

Add `--pbkdf-memory 1048576` to require 1 GB of RAM per unlock attempt, making GPU attacks significantly harder:

```bash
sudo cryptsetup luksFormat --type=luks2 --pbkdf argon2id --iter-time 4000 --pbkdf-memory 1048576 /dev/sdb
```

> Note: This requires 1 GB of free RAM on the machine unlocking the drive.

---

## Check Existing Drive Encryption

To inspect what LUKS version and KDF an already-encrypted drive uses:

```bash
sudo cryptsetup luksDump /dev/sdb
```

Look for the `Version:` and `PBKDF:` fields.

---

## ⚠️ Important Reminders

- **Back up your data before running `luksFormat`** — it wipes everything
- There is **no passphrase recovery** — if you forget it, the data is gone
- The drive will **not be readable on Windows** without third-party tools (e.g. LibreCrypt)
- Always safely eject / close the container before unplugging
